SIMPLE: dowry
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dowry
<hw>Dow"ry</hw> <pr>(dou"r⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Dowries</plw> <pr>(dou"r⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Contr. from
<ets>dowery</ets>; cf. LL. <ets>dotarium</ets>. See
<er>Dower</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A gift; endowment.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The money, goods, or estate, which a woman brings to
her husband in marriage; a bride's portion on her marriage. See Note
under <er>Dower</er>.</def> <rj><au>Shak. Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A gift or presents for the bride, on espousal. See
<er>Dower</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ask me never so much <qex>dowry</qex> and gift, and I will give .
. .; but give me the damsel to wife.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxxiv.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dowse</ent>⟦br⟧
